        "shloka": "tat kShEtram yat cha yAdr'k cha yat vikArI yata: cha yat |<br>sa cha yO yat prabhAva: cha tat samAsEna mE shr'Nu || 3 ||",
        "translation": "<span class='transliteration'>[tat kShEtram]</span><span class='sanskrit'>[\u0924\u0924\u094d \u0915\u094d\u0937\u0947\u0924\u094d\u0930\u092e\u094d]</span> That field of action - <span class='transliteration'>[yat cha]</span><span class='sanskrit'>[\u092f\u0924\u094d \u091a]</span> What is it made up of? <span class='transliteration'>[yAdr'k]</span><span class='sanskrit'>[\u092f\u093e\u0926\u0943\u0915\u094d]</span> What are its characteristics? <span class='transliteration'>[yat vikArI]</span><span class='sanskrit'>[\u092f\u0924\u094d \u0935\u093f\u0915\u093e\u0930\u0940]</span> What are its changes? <span class='transliteration'>[yata: cha]</span><span class='sanskrit'>[\u092f\u0924\u0903 \u091a]</span> What is its origin? <span class='transliteration'>[yat]</span><span class='sanskrit'>[\u092f\u0924\u094d]</span> What is its form? <span class='transliteration'>[sa cha]</span><span class='sanskrit'>[\u0938 \u091a]</span> Then we talked about the knower of the field - <span class='transliteration'>[ya:]</span><span class='sanskrit'>[\u092f\u0903]</span> What is his form? <span class='transliteration'>[yat prabhAva: cha]</span><span class='sanskrit'>[\u092f\u0924\u094d \u092a\u094d\u0930\u092d\u093e\u0935\u0903 \u091a]</span> What is his scope of influence? <span class='transliteration'>[tat mE shr'Nu]</span><span class='sanskrit'>[\u0924\u0924\u094d \u092e\u0947 \u0936\u0943\u0923\u0941]</span> Listen to it from Me <span class='transliteration'>[samAsEna]</span><span class='sanskrit'>[\u0938\u092e\u093e\u0938\u0947\u0928]</span> in summary.",
