            "The Self alone shines brilliant, even when it is among lamps, the sun and other bright things. It throws light on them - The Self is what makes the experience of brightness happen. Things that give light remove the darkness that blocks sight, nothing more. The Self alone recognizes and experiences brightness.<br>The word [tamas] used in this Shloka refers to the inanimate environment in its subtle state before creation. The environment doesn't have the capability to know and experience. <br>The Self is beyond the bounds of this environment.<br>The Self itself is awareness. We must recognize it. The Self can be grasped by practicing the virtues that were described in Chap.13#7-11, such as being without a sense of superiority. <br>The Self is specially embedded at the heart of all beings."
